This project is what inspired my Gear O' Clock gear profile. A very simple continuous .075 radius. Formula below for making your own... http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VHtRhu262zk Print out all or a few of the gears. Grab a mechanical pencil, Sharpie Pen, or an similar fine drawing utensils. Hold outer gear, place utensil in any one of the inner gears and draw many shapes. Feel free to use my design to make any new gear designs you wish. I only ask that you share working ones and upload them as derivatives. The designs can be endless. Squares, ovals, rectangles, blob shaped and any combination can be made. The diameter of the gear teeth is .15 inches. (See drawing.)
You must calculate pi by first determining how many teeth you want.
So basically 31 teeth x 2 = 62
62 x .15 = 9.3" which = The Circumference
9.3"/ pi = 2.962 which = the diameter to base your teeth off of.
The diameter refers to the pitch circle or center of diameter of your gear teeth.

I WANT YOU to make more designs and post them as derivatives!
The units are inches so don't complain they are not the proper size!

description.text:
If you need to paint or finish a part, paint cones are a must. They hold your part above the surface. They allow you to hold a wet part without marking it. They can hold spherical parts in place and stabilize compicated shaped ones. These are serious paint cones. Unlike cheap printable or commercial ones, those have all you want :
  • tetrahedron scalable shape for best stability
  • securable in place with screws
  • star shape (not pyramidal) to prevent overspray bouncing
  • heavy duty shape to hold both heavy and light parts even on 3 cones only
    • "A little upgrade after 10 months using them in loads of projects. The initial set printed as prototype is still in use. I printed 12 of them out of PLA, planning to upgrade some or replace damaged ones. I still have 6 brand new ones I never used, and the 6 in use are still working as new. So don't print spare parts if you don't need it. They're much stronger than expected and even working in heavy furniture projects and various types of solvent paint and varnishes, they don't damage at all. I believe it's a lifetime tool."

Printer Brand:

RepRap

Prusa I3

No

No

Best print : 0.3mm Nozzle, 0.2 layers, 4 walls, 6 layers for top and bottom

Infill:

100%

Notes: Print it for lifetime. Don't be cheap with infill, that cones don't need that much plastic anyways. In most cases you only need 3 cones to hold a part properly.

If you are lucky enough to have a dedicated finishing area secure them ! Unlike light and slippy ones, you can secure the serious paint cones in place with three 4mm screws (8x1). And you'll never get a cone sliding or falling again when moving your part.

At last here's trustable paint cones ! When I was a child, you could not find paint cones un general stores. So people just drive a nail out of a small offcut base, and that was our paint cones. But nails was hard enough to mark or scratch the wood. Actualy we get cheap paint cones from china. They're cheap, so they're light. You have trouble to get them in place, especialy when you move heavy parts over it. Several weeks ago, I was spaying some finish over a piece of furniture. It's a moment you want everythings to work perfectly. Any accident and you need to whait for the part to dry then go back to the sanding. This time one of my chinese paint cone just break under the weight of my furniture and the two other slips out. Of course my finishing was destroy instantly. Worst of all, a corner hit hardly the table and be damaged. Cheap paint cones are made to make money to the seller, not to get the job done properly. I promissed I'll never waste several hours of work again because of a stupid cheap piece of plastic. First I wanted the shape to be as stable as possible. Cheap chinese cones are too sharp. So the base is shorter than the height. It's not stable enough. Obviously the best shape for stability is the tetrahedron, which is better than any other shape for stability vs footprint, so here I've got the shape I want. Seccond I wanted the cone to be heavy duty to be strong enough for any purpose. Chinese cones uses thin walls. This is rubbish. I wanted strong walls so I drawed thick ones. To reduce printing time, I found that the star shape allows to reduce printing path while offering extra strenght : it's like 3 squares welded together on a large base. The star shape prevents overspray to bounce on the cone and reach the part too. Last, I wanted it to stay in place whatever you do. When you hold a heavy piece of furniture or have a wet part in front of you and a spray gun in hand, you don't want to worry about if one of your paint cones is still in place. So I wonder about what's the best way to secure a cone. Of course, as the bottom is flat, you can glue it or secure it with double sided tape. So I decided the bottom to be dead flat. But as time goes by any glue or tape can fail, especialy if you use paint or varnished that uses solvents. So I decided to put 3 countersik screw holes in the base. Even with time a screw will be hard to fail. I believe I came to the simplest possible shape, untill you want to keep all the purposes.

Scale the Serious Paint Cone to Match your needs I work most of the time life size parts, like pieces of art or furniture. By experience, I found a 30mm (which is between 1,1/8" and 1,1/4") was a good size to make a part strong enough for heavy parts I build. Anyways you can scale the cone to the size you need, if you work smaller or very large parts.

title: Serious Centre Finder
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
A centre finder is a common tool that allow you to find the centre of any cylindrical thing. The more round it is, the more precise will be the centre finder. On a log or any not totaly cylindrical thing you will draw multiple lines and be able to find an aproximative centre. 
The Serious Centre Finder is a trustable tool you can use at its original size to find centre of parts until a diameter of 254mm (10"). It's built strong to never bend in use and its reference corners are heavy duty. The tool have a beweled marking edge to allow a very precise drawing line. It's a lifetime tool.

Printer Brand:

RepRap

Printer:

Prusa I3

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

Best print : 0.3mm Nozzle, 0.2 layers, 4 walls, 6 layers for top and bottom

Infill:

50-100%

Notes: Don't be cheap with infill. Print a lifetime tool. Prefer PLA and avoid any softer material.
Don't try to clean the part, you can unstraight the part. If your printer is properly calibrated, you don't need anything, even if the first layer is too much squeeze out.

My old wooden centre finder just was no more acurate. I downloaded all centre finders I could found on Thingiverse. To be honnest, I was in a middle of a project and in hurry to find the centre of a wooden cylindre. I wasted a lot time to print unusable centre finders. Too small, too soft, bendable... Well I get a bit upset, none was realy usable trusty tools. So I opened my CAD program to redesign the wooden centre finder I made with my dad by the past. I undersized the lenght because I never had to used mine over very large pieces, and I wanted it to be printable on any standard printer. I oversized the walls to get a strong tool even if out of plastic. I also kept one very usefull feature : the bewel marking area which is very comfortable and accurate when you draw lines. When I designed it, this was the only Serious Centre Finder you can find on Thingiverse. If you don't own a centre finder, just print it out, keep it for life time, you'll be happy to have it on your shelf.

description.text:

comments.text: Just a tip. A stepper motor can reliably run at elevated temps all day long. Heat is NOT the problem. Adding mass is bad for the Y stage no matter how little you think it is. This causes more problems than it solves. Sorry, just being honest since I do design and build 3D printers.
comments.author: Unknown

comments.text: I've been using stepper motors in quite a few projects, and have repeatedly found that stepper motor torque decreases quite a lot once the case temperature passes 120F (which the drives on most of these printers do on medium to long prints). On my Makerbot Cupcake, it was almost impossible to complete a print over 2 hours long due to the Z axis stepper overheating and being unable to overcome the friction in the drive rods and the weight of the platform. I had a similar issue on all three vertical drives of my Rostock Max in the beginning, but have since installed heatsyncs on both and they are now running just fine, even for very long prints. I agree that adding mass to the already heavy Y stage is bad, but in this case, I think it would be well worth it. The only downside is that acceleration and deceleration rates must be adjusted accordingly to avoid missed steps and vibration if the mass increase is high enough.
comments.author: Unknown

comments.text: Additionally, If the heat sinks help retain their torque than perhaps they earn their weight added to the gantry. So long as the load is lite.

description.text:
This is a very helpful item for your XL20 or XL21 Xlerator Wheel stand using the Logitech G29 or G920 racing wheel. The power adapter is hard to move around not attached to the stand. A pair of these clamps and holders will let you mount the power box up to the stand making it easier to move, store and play.
Each clamp uses (2) two 10-24 x 1" machine screws and nuts (10-32 thread will work also). The nuts are held inside the clamp in slots. To use the clamp, attach it to the stand, then slide the box into it. It is a force fit so the box won't move. Then slide it and tighten it down where you want it.
The adapter for the Logitech G29 and I am assuming the Logitech G920 have a power adapter that measures 4.28" long 2.27" high and 1.26" tall. This power adapter I am sure will work with other power boxes for Thrustmaster and Fanatec. It will probably work with the Logitech G25, G27 and GT also. If you need another size let me know and I will adapt this design to your size box and list it on here.

Each piece has to be printed 16 times, at the exception of the support (6th picture).
WATCH OUT: you might find it beautiful, but it's a nightmare to build (more than 20 hours assembly). 
I post this object mostly to see how skilled people could make it more mechanically build-able. And also to give you some inspirations, and some lesson-learned about one of my first designs.
Note: you have to drill one square holes at the top of two opposed meridians to insert the support. A nylon tie on the electric wire avoids the support to glide down.

Comments and Advices The goal is to have a globe, with meridians and parallels, where light is diffused either through, or reflected by the very thin plastic (0.3 mm), but whatever you position, you cannot see the bulb and be blinded.
My first design attempt was to print one meridian flat on the bed, and to raise the parallels during the same print. This was a failure since single layer walls tends to wobble after 1 cm high. After a few attempts, I arrived to the design you see, with the meridian in 2 parts (for my 22*22 cm bed). I used Sketchup, and provide here the 3DS file. I extracted the flat items from this model, and extruded each piece to give them volume. Each piece is printed with an infinite number of walls (in facts, 350), in order to get a nice concentric pattern instead of a parallel filling. It could be interesting to use a large nozzle (0.6 mm?), to obtain an even more graphic structure. Assembling directly the (16*15=240) panels on the meridian was quite a pain in the harsh (pun intended)... I used thin CA glue for assembly, with a very convenielnt accelerator in a spray (see hobbyist websites for cheap supply). But since objects made with a single layer are not at the exact mesure (your printer usually have 150-200% feed for the first layer, to assure that it stick to the bed), each piece tends to be bigger. And each minor error adds one after the other, so when you finish the circle with 16 pieces, you are not good at all. If you force you bend some pieces, and you see on the pictures that everything is not perfectly straight; I had to cut some pieces smaller (with simple scissors!), for some others, I had to make them bigger. So my suggestion for whoever would be interested to redo my masterpiece:
  • The parallels should insert in slots on both sides, instead of being guided by a single "step" on one side. You could duplicate each meridian, mirror those, so that when glued back to back, you can have protruding parts on both sides, without needing supports.
  • The parallels should be designed a bit smaller than needed, the play being hidden in the slots
  • It might be also very useful and time saving to design two positioning rigs for the meridians (for top and bottom), with slots every 360/16=22.5°, to be assured everything is well positioned before you start the irreversible gluing.
  • You could also try with coarser round shape. Here the circle has been approximated with 16 straight lines. You could try with 12, having then much less pieces to assemble.
    • Other Warning: I started the printing with a white PLA with no brand, and then finished my roll. I bought some famous-branded PLA, but this one is much more opaque. I didn't dare to go below 0.2 mm, and it's still quite denser in tint than the previous one. Another idea: You could print out only one copy of each parallels, and use those as templates to cut out all of them in another material, like translucend semi-rigid plastic sheets (often used by designers) or acrylic sheets (those used for building green houses), or... Sorry for my mistakes in English, this is not my native language...

description.text:
Block insert and outer shroud need to make a Low-D PVC Tinwhistle/Pennywhistle.
Low D is the first D note above Middle C on a piano
Requires 24" of 3/4" PVC pipe, SDR21 grade (thin wall, do not use Sched 40)
Go easy on the print speed, otherwise it will deform. Get some very thin (watery) superglue for this.

Printer Brand:

Rafts:

Notes: Go easy on printing speed

Assembling a pennywhistle Cut 3/4" PVC pipe to approx 24 inches long. (note, to Europeans and those not familiar with PVC, it's called 3/4" but there is nothing there that is actually 3/4" diameter). Using a hacksaw, cut out a 1/2" by 1.43" rectangular slot on one end of the PVC pipe. Using a file, file out a ramp for the windway as shown in the photos. Clean up the pieces from the printer before installing. Slide the insert with it's 1/2" notch in alignment with the 1/2" notch.
Then slide the outer shroud piece over the PVC pipe and also align the 1/2" notch. The diagonal portion should face away from the pipe.
Line of the lips of the two pieces in the airway hole.
Try to get a sound out of it, when you are happy with the sound, secure the two pieces using super glue.
Then using a tuner, see what note you get. You'll need to trim away from the bottom until you get a well tuned Low-D note.
Then it's time to make tone holes:
I'm giving the diameter of the holes in inches and the position from the bottom to the center of each hole in inches. Note, you might have to tweak the holes diameter a little after drilling and also clean up the plastic bits on the other side of the hole. For Low-D:
15/64" 101mm
7/16" 146mm
3/8" 163mm
5/16" 222mm
3/8" 256mm
3/8" 295mm For other keys with this design, consult "Low Whistle Makers Anthology".

History I originally design the PVC whistle using PVC fittings and a block of acetal cut out on the lathe. I've been making whistles since 1998. The age of 3D printers has made the most difficult part of the pennywhistle easy to make.
The shapes are made using OpenSCAD, being a computer programmer I find OpenSCAD very appealing.

description.text:
Bought the DROK TDA7297 stereo amplifier for my old Mod B pi
Bloomin! amazing value for money and sound quality, IF have suitable 12V power supply and old speakers. They are widely available on both Amazon and ebay here's one link:
http://www.ebay.com/sch/sis.html?_nkw=DROK+TDA7297+Mini+Digital+Amplifier+Stereo+Audio+Ampli+Electro+12+Volt+Amp+New&_trksid=p2047675.m4100 But they have two problems
  • No case
  • No balance control
    • Well created case, but its available else where (sorry need the cash)
    https://www.3dagogo.com/3dagogo/designs/natkoAMPCASE Now balance control is harder, the amplifier is a bridge type which for me means the output can not be easily altered (well on the cheep) . So made this add on to provide balance control for my DROK TDA7297 case.
    It's a lot more technical than just the case so decided to post it here.
    The files create an add on case that takes the input and balances that in what I hope is a stylish manner. The electrical explanation is here (see fig 9)
    http://sound.westhost.com/pots.htm I used the 100k Pot and 33k resisters as exampled, with a standard stereo male and female jack's available from local stores (one of each).
    You will also need 2 off - 3mm by 10mm screws. I hope to create an additional module that you could add additional inputs (bit like a mixer just add the module for each input you want)... but need to research if isolation required ??? Please note this is fiddly as hell wiring wise, definitely pre solder the wires onto the male jack before screwing in, as no space to solder once screwed in. If you want to add feet they are 13mm inserts that will need levering out with small flat screw driver and the bottom thing needs a 3mm drill bit run down the holes.

Since this technology is new, I find many educators(with their plates already full) that are skeptical of the 3D printers value in the classroom with the time it takes to print objects. For myself, I placed academics second to inspiration where I enticed students with what a printer could do "for them"(i.e. trinkets, toys, nameplates, models of the Eiffel Tower). For a unit on scale and ratio, 3D modelling is great.  I envision demonstrating to students the wonder of 3D printing by showing them a number of models I've previously created.  Some of them being architectural or monuments around the world. As they ooh and ahh over them, we'll begin to talk about scale and how I achieved creating these models by scaling them down a certain percentage of their actual size. After some more examples of scaling and demonstrating the math involved in scaling, students will have the opportunity to research a certain piece of notable architecture or a monument around the world.  They will then learn to scale these models down to a certain size, let's say 12 in. tall.  These types of lessons would continually give students hands-on experience in scaling models to suitable sizes for various projects.

I found after several months, the tines dezbot's would tend to fatigue, delaminate and break off from the back plate. This holder is structured so that that it can be printed vertically and thus the tines aren't susceptible to breaking along layer boundaries. I believe this design will last significantly longer. While I haven't tried PLA, I suspect ABS is the superior material for this part since it tends to be more flexible. Update: I had problems with the tines fatiguing, even with the new print orientation. At its narrowest point, each tine had only 2 widths of plastic on my Printrbot. I've made them much wider so that they now have 4 + some fill.

• Print the "Tiny Toothbrush Holder - Print Oriented.stl"
  • Mount to wall with a #6 countersink wood screw (0.25" long should be sufficient if mounting into wood, 0.5" or more is best for mounting into plaster)
